The resulting charm  cross section is shown in Fig. \ref{fig:comparexF} for an incident proton energy $E_p=10^6$ GeV. The forward component is shown along with the central component dominated by the subprocess $gg \rightarrow c \bar{c}$, Eq. (\ref{eq:gg}). While the active charm component represents a subdominant contribution to the central production of charmed particles, the spectator contribution dominates for x-values above 0.2. The spectator charm effectively becomes a valence quark during this interaction, resulting in the forward production. Note that perturbative QCD  generates a forward component of the charm cross section without resorting to intrinsic charm. The subprocess effectively promotes the spectator charm to a valence quark. The phenomenology is therefore similar to that of intrinsic charm quarks in the proton and we do not anticipate that an analysis modeling intrinsic charm will lead to different conclusions.

